,Recommended,232910,34386985,Posted: 20 August,all,Anonymate,"What this game is and is not about.1.This is NOT a F1 simulator.You drive a F1 car and that's as close as it gets. Expect to be running in dirt tracks (yeap, those used in rally races), going through vertical loops and even floating on air. Yes, you will be jumping and ""flying"" a lot.2.You DO NOT race against other players;or even against bots. You just race alone trying to get better and better times. In solo, you just try to break your own record, as well as local/national/world records for each official track. In multiplayer, you just try to get a better time than the other players: you can try as many times as you wish before the time ends and the track is changed; you also see the other players trying, but only as ghosts (no direct interaction).3.The physics are NOT even close to reality.You can literally accelerate, break and even turn while floating on air (although these cause a much smaller effect than doing those on the ground). Your car doesn't suffer any damage when you hit a wall. Also good to point out that the gravity is much lower than Earth's gravity. Don't get me wrong, I do enjoy it; that doesn't make it any more realistic.The current problems with the game1. In the past, you could just download the game and start playing. Now, before you start the game, you must register in their website before you can connect, and then download some huge updates in-game using their servers (instead of steam servers). It's annoying and you may need to access the community discussions in order to learn how to register (at least when I did, the in-game instructions did not work - for me or anybody else - and I'm not sure if they fixed it).There are other minor issues not worth pointing out here. Unfortunately, from what I've seen, new bugs are created and older ones are not fixed. The game doesn't suffer from any major issue though.Other than that, I'm under the impression that they still have devs working on the game and it's still fun to spend some time (I usually connect, play on a single track for 10 to 20 minutes and quit)."
