,Not Recommended,232910,17675539,"Posted: 23 August, 2015",all,Luparax,"Okay, so, I have to warn you before I begin this review. I am biased. Against TM2 (Track Mania 2) and towards TMU (Track Mania United). Let me tell you why.Review of Track Mania 2 : StadiumSo, before I begin delving into the depth of deprivation, let me tell you that this is essentially ""Track Mania United - Stadium"". Except TMU came with 6 other areas, which are essentially ""themes"", you could play in.Price Comparison:TMU - Star Edition --> 29.99€ (seven areas + some small extras)TM2 - Stadium       -->  9.99€ (one area)TM2 - Stadium + TM2 - Valley + TM2 - Canyon --> 39,99€ (three areas)I am a little speechless. And in order to prevent myself from getting a headache, I will treat the rest of the review as if that is not a giant rip off.A fair reviewer treats games independently. The 6th iteration in a series need not necessarily be worse than the 1st. And I would give TM2 - Stadium the benefit of the doubt, if it weren't for the fact that it is an exact copy of the TMU stadium area. The size of the stadium, the pieces that are used to build the tracks, even the color of the grass if it isn't stuck on a darker shade again for a couple of blocks because screw unified grass colors. That would be silly, right? I could of course just be a giant doof and missed the ""Unify grass colors again"" button, but I believe there is none. There is but a single set of road pieces that got added from the last iteration of TM.Maybe I should have expected that, when I bought a TM game with the name ""Stadium"". But I didn't excpect a company to be as cocky as to sell an area they sold before for another 10 bucks and call it ""Track Mania 2"". But Nadeo just laughs a ""Think again!"" in my face.GameplayTrack Mania is about driving on courses built with an open level editor. It is about driving a course over and over and over again until you can beat that sweet gold medal time. It's about building your own tracks, and watching your friends drive into walls you placed at inconvenient locations.Track Mania is a racing game with essentially infinite levels, built with the same +100 pieces. It is fun, it is competitive and it is exciting.For those of you who don't know the TM Series yet: It's not a game where you can crash into other people. You'll be always driving against their ""ghost"". TM is about finding that ideal path through a course, not about pushing other people off the track.The controls are as simple as you can get. Arrow keys to control your car, backspace to respawn at the last checkpoint. These are rebindable, of course. You can also use a gamepad which allows for precise driving with the analog stick. I personally prefer the keyboard, because the TM tracksusually are about trying to find the ideal path in a course, and analog input is hard to repeat perfectly every time you try again. It seems to me that the game engine and car physics have been tweaked to accomodate analog input more, which makes the cars drift a lot when using digital input i.e. the keyboard. That is more of a problem with the other areas and not so much with stadium, so I will not consider that as a disadvantage for this game.There is no split screen option, as far as I am aware. Local players have to take turns. There never has been a split screen option in any of the TM games. I don't know why, because it is a fun game to play against friends locally; racing games in general are.To conclude all of the above: The gameplay is solid. The game executes what it wants to do perfectly.GraphicsPeople say, TM2 has really nice graphics. Be prepared to drop some frames on crowded tracks though if you crank them up to the highest setting. In addition to that arguably small flaw, I had to consult the internet to find a way to change graphics settings in the launcher. Apparently, pressing ""Customize"" does not allow you to change graphics settings. Setting the preset to ""None"" does. Again, a small flaw. Overall the games graphics do not have to hide from the big players.Conclusion: Great graphics, small flaws in the execution.Singleplayer vs MultiplayerI felt like this needed an extra category. While the game has a ""singleplayer"" campaign and unless you have friends who also play the game, the real fun comes in beating other peoples times. Of course there is no lobby system, since you only every try to beat their time or drive against their ""ghost"" if you will.The single player campaign is slightly flawed in my eyes. Gold Medal now actually means ""Gold Medal"", even on the first track of the first part of the campaign. There is no increase in difficulty when it comes to the times you have to beat, they will always be tough. There will be an increase of the skill you need to traverse a track though, which in my eyes is just about enough for a racing game single player campaign. Of course there is no story or anything apart from the tracks, but in a game like TM2 I did not miss that.Conclusion: Single player is solid and demanding. Multiplayer in the classic meaning does not exists, but you will be comparing your track time to other peoples time constantly.VerdictI don't see anything that TMU does not provide. TM2 might not be a bad game, but in my eyes it adds nothing the the TM ""Genre"" as a whole. If you like the slightly better graphics get TM2 over TMU. For anyone else I recommend buying TMU, especially since you get more bang bang bang bang bang bang bang for buck."
