,Not Recommended,232910,11442518,"Posted: 27 July, 2014",all,harrythecat01 [Director's Cut],"Yes, it's popular. Yes, it's kind of fun. Yet its physics are disapppointingly despondent towards drifting and have a numbing feeling in general. The cars are also programmed to be mortal enemies towards any wall, making it impossible to recover your race after a single mistake or botched turn. The game seems to be geared towards racing AI that always knows the right line to take. This makes playing the game agitating, tedious, and stressful. Also, there is an extremely annoying and obvious lack of any learning curve at all, as if the game expects you to be a pro-TrackMania player with hundreds of hours logged as soon as you start playing. This once again points to the idea that the game is designed for computers. The basic level editor allows the choice of, quite literally, less than 10 pieces and seems to be designed for toddlers. This is in stark contrast to the advanced level editor, which gives absolutely no direction as to how to use its nonsensical pre-race footage editing tools and seems to expect you to compute shadows every time you edit a map, a process that can take 10+ minutes with all the computations forgotten by the file even after you save the map. There is also no option for car-on-car collision, allowing them to pathetically phase through one another. The game also requires intimate router port forwarding knowledge in order to use several customization functions, which is something I spent all day trying to figure out. Generally the ports are forwarded by the .exe install file instead. Moreover, there is no boost, very few graphics and audio options, and a completely stupid currency system. This is only a portion of the things I have a problem with, but I'll spare the rest. In short, this game is great for people who love experiencing repeated failure, but a dismal waste to all others."
